SIMPLE: moir
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Moir
<hw>Moi`r⟦eacute⟧"</hw> <pr>(mw⟦aum⟧`r⟦amac⟧";
m⟦omac⟧"r⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A watered,
clouded, or frosted appearance on textile fabrics or metallic
surfaces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Erroneously, moire, the fabric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A wavy pattern of lines produced by the
superposition of two patterns having closely spaced, often curved,
lines, so that the lines of the two patterns intersect at an acute
angle. When the superposing patterns are moved relative to the observer
or relative to each other, a shimmering effect is produced in which the
apparent pattern changes, often producing a pleasing artistic effect.
The effect may be seen, for example, when the superposed folds of a
sheer fabric, such as a window curtain, are observed with transmitted
light.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> moire pattern.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Printing)</fld> <def>An interference pattern
produced by the dots of a color printing process.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Moire antique</b></col>, <cd>a superior kind of thick
moire.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Moir
<hw>Moi`r⟦eacute⟧"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[F., p.p.
of <ets>moirer</ets> to water (silk, etc.). See <er>Moire</er>.]</ety>
<def>Watered; having a watered or clouded appearance; -- as of silk or
metals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Moire</ent>⟦br⟧

